b'' b'q: if you knew beyond all doubt that hell did not exist and that' b' unbelievers simply remained dead, would you remain a christian?' b'' b'interesting question, esp since i remember *wishing* with all' b"my heart that this *were* true so that i wouldn't have to be a" b'"good christian" anymore. "christianity" was terribly hard, the' b'only reward was heaven and (maybe, sometimes, if i was really' b'good) acceptance; i wanted a way out.' b'' b'if you knew this "beyond all doubt", then you would be foolish to be' b'a disciple of a man who claimed it did exist. the truth is, you can' b"not be jesus' disciple and disagree with him at the same time, not" b'allowing him to be your "lord".' b'' b'what jesus has done for me since i found him (some months ago)' b'i do not want to lose. period.' b'' b'that said, i originally interpreted the what-if as "if christ' b'never mentioned sheol and weeping and gnashing of teeth, if' b'christ preached that those who did not follow him died and stayed' b'dead and at that point forever ceased to exist...."' b'' b'....fear-based religion is not a faith-relationship with the' b"one who made us all. i follow christ because it's a great way" b'to live life. and i could care less what really happens after' b'i die. b'' b"so is being a buddhist a great way to live life. i'm not converting," b'though.' b'' b'i believe that we can only be complete through christ.' b'do you think that buddhists can also be complete?' b'' b'-jen' b'' b'--' b'' 